Denote by (\alpha) the part {(x + \sqrt[3]{x + \sqrt[3]{x + \dotsb}})}. Then we have \[\alpha = \sqrt[3]{x + \alpha}\] Thus, \[\alpha^3 = x + \alpha \Longrightarrow \alpha^3 - \alpha = x.\]
Now denote by (\beta) the part {(x \sqrt[3]{x \sqrt[3]{x \dotsm}})}. Then we have \[\beta = \sqrt[3]{x\beta}\] Thus, \[\beta^3 = x\beta \Longrightarrow \beta^2 = x.\]\[ \therefore \alpha = \beta^2.\] From the above notice that we have \(\alpha = x + \beta\) and \(\alpha = \beta^2\) while \(\alpha\), \(\beta > 0.\) Then we can write \[\beta^2 = x + \beta \Longrightarrow \beta^2 = \alpha + \beta \Longrightarrow \beta^2 - \beta - \beta^2 = 0 \Longrightarrow \beta = 1.\] Therefore, \(x = 1.\) <answer>bingo! I found the positive solution\end{document}
